  "title": "Linear Functions",
  "body": " Linear Functions     What is the difference between a linear function and a proportional relationship?   How is the equation of a linear function related to its graph?  What do solutions to linear equations represent graphically?     There are some families of functions that describe very common relationships. We will study a few of these families in this section, Section , and Section .    The table of a function is given below. Compute , , and , recalling Subsection as needed.                                    Linear and Proportional Relationships  You should have found in Warm-Up that no matter which interval you chose, was the same number. This property is the defining characteristic of linear functions:   Linear Function  linear function  function linear A linear function is a function such that is constant for every two values and in the domain of the function.  If a function has a constant average rate of change, we can say something very specific about the equation for the function. For suppose is a linear function. Then we know that for any value, the average rate of change between and is constant (call it ). That is,   We can re-write as  , or  .  Linear Function Equation  The equation of a linear function in linear function slope-intercept form  slope-intercept form is . The value is called the slope of the function, and the value is called the -intercept .  The equation of a linear function in linear function point-slope form  point-slope form is . The value is the slope of the function, and is any point on the graph of the function.   A related concept is that of a proportional relationship , which we define next.   Proportional Relationship  proportional  proportional proportionality constant  A quantity is proportional to a quantity if they are related by the equation , where is a parameter. The value is called the proportionality constant .    Linear and Proportional Relationships  The function is a linear function with slope and -intercept .  The function represents a proportional relationship. is proportional to with proportionality constant .    Determine whether each table below represents a linear relationship, proportional relationship, or neither.                                                                                                                                             Graphs of Linear Relationships  Notice that in the equation of a linear function , the slope is the constant average rate of change of the function. We can use our previous knowledge about average rates of change from Subsection and transformations from Subsection to help us understand the graphical behavior of linear functions.   Let be a linear function.  First, use concepts from Subsection to complete the sentences below. Then use the interactive provided to support your answers.  No matter the value of , the graph of is always...  If , then the graph of ...  If , then the graph of ...  If , then the graph of ...  If is very large in absolute value, then the graph of ...  If is very small in absolute value, then the graph of ...     With as your parent function, use concepts from Subsection to complete the sentences below. Then use the interactive provided to support your answers.  If , then the graph of ...  If , then the graph of ...  If , then the graph of ...           Solutions of Linear Equations  A linear equation  linear equation is any equation involving only linear functions. A linear equation solution  solution to a linear equation is any value that makes the equation true.   Linear Equations and Solutions  The equation is a linear equation. A solution to this equation is since . This solution could be found algebraically by solving for :    Given two linear functions and , finding a solution to the linear equation means finding an value when the associated values on each line are equal. Graphically, this means finding a point of intersection.   Solutions to Linear Equations Graphically  In Example , we saw that a solution to the linear equation is . Graphically, this means if we graphed and , there would be an intersection point at :   A graph of two lines intersecting at x equal two.     Give an example of a linear equation for each scenario below, or explain why an example does not exist. You are encouraged to think about each scenario graphically.  A linear equation which has exactly one solution.  A linear equation which has no solution.  A linear equation which has two solutions.  A linear equation in which every number is a solution.       Summary    What is the difference between a linear function and a proportional relationship?  A linear function is a function relationship which has a constant average rate of change between any two points. A proportional relationship is a specific type of linear function in which the - intercept is equal to .    How is the equation of a linear function related to its graph?  The graph of a linear function can be determined by its slope and -intercept. The slope determines whether the graph increases or decreases, and how quickly it increases or decreases. The -intercept is a vertical shift of the graph of which determines where the graph crosses the -axis.    What do solutions to linear equations represent graphically?  Solutions to linear equations are points of intersection when graphing the lines on the left and right of the sign. It is possible to have exactly one solution, no solution, or infinitely many solutions.       Give an example, or explain why no example exists, of the graph of a function which is  linear but not proportional.  proportional but not linear.  linear and proportional.      Write the equation of the line that passes through the points and using  point-slope form.  slope-intercept form.            Find the solution(s) to , where is a parameter (your answer will be something in terms of ). For what value(s) of is there no solution?   ,     Let be a linear function representing the price (in dollars) for riding miles.  What are the units of ?  What are the units of ?      dollars  dollars\/mile      "
