  "title": "Limits: Leading Behaviors",
  "body": " Limits: Leading Behaviors  leading behaviors    How can we evaluate complicated limits as ?  How can we evaluate complicated limits as ?     In this section we continue with the general goal of Section : evaluating limits. In this section we will focus on limit at infinity  limits at infinity , which have the form . These are important for determining the end behavior of a function, which can tell us how a system behaves in the long run. They can help us answer questions like is the population headed towards extinction? and what is the baseline concentration of a substance in the bloodstream? . We were introduced to basic limits of this form in Subsection . In this section, we will use the method of leading behaviors to help us evaluate more complicated limits at infinity.      Graph and in Desmos. Compare and contrast the graphs that you see. What is the same? What is different?  Graph and in Desmos. Compare and contrast the graphs that you see. What is the same? What is different?  Graph in Desmos. What is ? Why do you think this is the limit's value, and how could you determine this value just using the equation of ?      Leading Behavior at  In Warm-Up we observed a complicated function built as the sum of simpler functions can exhibit local behavior that is complicated to predict without computation, like its zeros and its local extrema. However, if we are interested in describing the end behavior of such a function, as we are in this section, it can be predicted based on the behavior of a single simpler function. Indeed, if , and dominates and as , then the graph of will start to behave like the graph of as . For such a function, we give the dominant term a special name.   leading behaviors at  The leading behavior of at  Let be a sum of functions. If one function in the sum dominates all of the other functions in the sum in absolute value as , we call this function the leading behavior of at . We denote the leading behavior of at as .   Note that leading behavior is determined by which term dominates in absolute value . A term being positive or negative can impact the value of the limit, but it does not effect whether or not a term is the leading behavior. As we described above, the leading behavior of a function at can be useful in evaluating limits at infinity:   Leading Behavior at  Let be a function with leading behavior at  . Then .   The benefit of leading behaviors is that it allows us to replace a complicated function with a simpler one that has the same end behavior.   Leading Behavior at  Let and . In Section we determined that as , exponential growth dominates power growth dominates logarithmic growth. Therefore, we know that , since dominates the other terms as . Also, since exponential growth dominates power function growth. We must be careful to notice here that the leading behavior at infinity is not , since this function decays to as .  We could also use leading behaviors to evaluate the limit of the ratio of and : , since dominates as .    For each function pair below, first determine and . Then evaluate .  ,   ,   ,        Leading Behavior at  Leading behavior at is defined similarly to leading behavior at :  leading behaviors at  The leading behavior of at  Let be a sum of functions. If one function in the sum dominates all of the other functions in the sum in absolute value as , we call this function the leading behavior of at . We denote the leading behavior of at as .    We can also use similarly to help us evaluate limit as :  Leading Behavior at  Let be a function with leading behavior at  . Then .  The main thing we must be careful of with leading behaviors at is to pay attention to the behavior of the function as ; that is, as we move to the left on the graph of the function. This behavior is in general different than the behavior as (as we move to the right on the graph of the function). For example, is a common leading behavior at because it is exponential growth, and gets large quickly as . However, it is not a common leading behavior at since it decays to as : .   Leading Behavior at  Let and . Then , since dominates the other terms as . For , note that gets very small as . The function gets very large as , but is power function growth. The function grows exponentially as . Thus, .  We can use leading behaviors to evaluate the limit of the ratio of and : , since dominates as .    For each function pair below, first determine and . Then evaluate .  ,   ,   ,        Summary   How can we evaluate complicated limits as ?   To evaluate limits of the form , we can determine if has a leading behavior at , . If so, we know .    How can we evaluate complicated limits as ?   To evaluate limits of the form , we can determine if has a leading behavior at , . If so, we know .        Let .  Determine .  Evaluate .  Determine .  Evaluate .              Determine the equation of a function that satisfies each set of criteria below. Justify why your equation satisfies the criteria using leading behaviors.  A function such that and .  A function such that and .      "
